) VALUES (
  'chongqing_republican_citywalk',
  'chongqing',
  'Chongqing''s Time Capsule: A Citywalk Through Republican-Era Architecture',
  '民国建筑 Citywalk',
  'Chongqing served as China''s wartime capital during the Republican era (1912–1949), and it still holds one of the country''s richest collections of buildings from that period.',
  '🚶',
  'Citywalk',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p>Chongqing served as China''s wartime capital during the Republican era (1912–1949), and it still holds one of the country''s richest collections of buildings from that period. Historic mansions, former government offices, old foreign consulates, and early modern banks—many blending Chinese and Western design—climb the city''s steep hills, cling to its river cliffs, and stand alongside today''s skyscrapers. Several of these districts have been well preserved, and they feel less like museums than like ordinary neighborhoods that happen to carry a great deal of history.</p><p>Walking through them gives you a sense of Chongqing in the 1930s and 1940s, when the city was a hub of Allied activity in the China-Burma-India theater of World War II. You can visit former residences of wartime figures, sites tied to the era''s political negotiations, old consulate buildings, and narrow stone lanes where merchants, students, and intellectuals once mixed. What sets Chongqing''s Republican architecture apart is how closely it is tied to the city''s dramatic mountain-and-river setting—buildings step up hillsides and follow the slope of the land in a way you rarely see elsewhere.</p><p>Ready to explore Chongqing''s Republican past? Here are four historic districts worth putting on your itinerary.</p><h2>1. Zhongshan Fourth Road: The Political Heart of Wartime Chongqing</h2><p>*A leafy street lined with former residences, old government offices, and sites connected to major political events of the era. A good starting point for anyone interested in China''s wartime history.*</p><h2>What to see and do</h2><p>Zhongshan Fourth Road is one of Chongqing''s best-preserved Republican-era streets, running for close to a kilometer. It is shaded by tall banyan (Huangjue) trees, whose canopy scatters sunlight across the pavement. On both sides stand rows of brick-and-timber buildings—mansions with grey-tiled roofs, red-brick walls, and arched doorways, many set back behind courtyard greenery. These are original structures rather than replicas.</p><p>Here you can visit <strong>Gui Yuan</strong>, a former general''s residence where the Double Tenth Agreement was signed in 1945, an early step toward negotiations between the Chinese Communist Party and the Kuomintang. Nearby is the <strong>Zhougong Guan (Zhou Enlai''s Former Office and Residence)</strong>, where original office furnishings, telephones, and typewriters are still on display. The <strong>Museum of the History of China''s Democratic Parties</strong>, housed in a large period mansion, holds a collection of historical photographs, documents, and artifacts.</p><p>The district is calm and unhurried. Walking the tree-lined paths, with the smell of old brick and foliage in the air, is a fitting way to begin a tour of Chongqing''s Republican past.</p><h2>2. Longmenhao Old Street: River Views and Consulate History</h2><p>*A hillside district with former consulate and bank buildings, sweeping river views, and a relaxed atmosphere. Popular with photographers and anyone who enjoys older architecture.*</p><h2>What to see and do</h2><p>Longmenhao Old Street is one of the larger and better-preserved historic districts in central Chongqing. It sits on the south bank of the Yangtze in Nan''an District, built into the foothills and overlooking the river. The layout follows the city''s mountain topography: narrow cobblestone lanes rise and fall with the slope, and the buildings are stacked in tiers, rarely sharing the same level.</p><p>The district is known for its cluster of Republican-era consulate and bank buildings. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, this area was home to many of the foreign consulates, banks, and businesses then operating in Chongqing. The architecture mixes Western influences with local hillside construction—brick buildings with stone columns and arched windows, alongside smaller villas with carved wooden window frames and stonework, most built with local stone and set into the slope.</p><p>Look for the <strong>former U.S. Military Attaché''s Office</strong>, a preserved building that now presents the history of Chongqing''s foreign contacts during this period. (If you plan to reference the building''s exact former function, it''s worth confirming on site, as sources describe it variously.) Walk the cliffside plank path partway up the hillside for a wide view of the Yangtze, the Dongshuimen Bridge, and the skyline of the Yuzhong peninsula—a good vantage point for photos of the city''s mix of old and new. For more historical context, the <strong>"Chongqing·1937" immersive theater</strong> stages a live drama inside a period building.</p><p>In the evening, the street lamps come on and light up the old buildings and stone lanes. You can sit at an open-air café on one of the terraces, order a coffee, and watch the light change over the river.</p><h2>3. Liziba–Sanma Road: Mountain-City Architecture and Wartime Sites</h2><p>*An area that shows off Chongqing''s vertical "mountain city" terrain, with preserved Republican-era mansions and government buildings—plus the well-known sight of a monorail line running through a residential tower.*</p><h2>What to see and do</h2><p>The Liziba–Sanma Road area is one of the clearest illustrations of Chongqing''s three-dimensional layout. The Republican-era buildings here are mainly former residences of wartime military and political figures. Rather than sitting on level ground, they are built into cliffs and steep slopes, with large differences in elevation across a single site—partly for security during the war, and partly a natural response to the terrain.</p><p>Follow the stone-paved Sanma Road ("Three Horses Road") as it winds uphill; this was once an important route linking the upper city with the river port. Along the way you''ll pass preserved mansions, including the <strong>Gao Family Mansion</strong>, a two-story brick-and-timber former residence, and the <strong>Liu Family Mansion</strong>, built high on the slope with views over the river valley.</p><p>A highlight is the <strong>Liziba wartime heritage park</strong>, which gathers relocated and restored Republican-era buildings, several moved here from other parts of the city. From the park you can also catch the well-known view of <strong>Monorail Line 2 passing directly through a residential building</strong>—a piece of urban engineering that Chongqing has become famous for. Cliffside paths and viewing platforms nearby look out over the river, the Yuzhong peninsula, and the surrounding hills.</p><p>*(A quick note on names: I''ve kept the river and heritage-park names as they appeared in your draft. Place names like these are easy to garble in translation, so it''s worth double-checking the official English spellings before publishing.)*</p><h2>4. Liangjiang International Film City (Republic of China Street): Step Back in Time</h2><p>*A film-and-television theme park with a recreated Republican-era streetscape. The most hands-on, family-friendly stop on this list—you can rent period costumes, watch performances, and take photos on a large open-air set.*</p><h2>What to see and do</h2><p>If you''d rather experience the era in a more playful, interactive way, Liangjiang International Film City is worth a visit. It''s a purpose-built set that recreates Chongqing''s streets and buildings from the 1930s and 40s, down to the shop signs, street lamps, and brick detailing. The effect is a bit like walking onto a movie backlot.</p><p>The main "Old Street" is lined with recreated period buildings—government offices, Western-style restaurants, barber shops, department stores, and a reproduction of the wartime Victory Monument. The set was built from historical archives, old photographs, and city maps, so it aims to resemble Chongqing''s old commercial center.</p><p>The draw here is dressing up and taking part. You can rent a cheongsam, a Zhongshan suit, or a student''s uniform from on-site shops, add period accessories like a leather satchel or a paper umbrella, and wander the streets for photos. The park is also used to film period dramas, so you may occasionally see a crew at work.</p><p>Throughout the day there are <strong>live performances</strong> on the streets that visitors can join—street parades, staged ceremonies, and similar. You can also try traditional crafts such as tie-dyeing and cloth-weaving in the workshops, or watch an old film in the restored Taihe Theater.</p><p>It''s a light, enjoyable way to round off a tour of the era''s architecture, with plenty of photo opportunities.</p><h2>Practical Information</h2><h3>Getting there</h3><p>Chongqing is well connected by air and rail, and its metro system makes the districts in this guide easy to reach.</p><ul><li><strong>Zhongshan Fourth Road:</strong> Take Rail Transit Line 2 or Line 10 to <strong>Zengjiayan Station</strong> (Exit C); the street is about a 5-minute walk. Alternatively, take the metro to <strong>Niujiaotuo Station</strong> (Exit 4) and walk about 400 meters.</li><li><strong>Longmenhao Old Street:</strong> Take Line 6 or the Loop Line to <strong>Shangxinjie Station</strong> (Exit 1); the main entrance is about a 5-minute walk.</li><li><strong>Liziba–Sanma Road:</strong> Take Line 2 or Line 10 to <strong>Liziba Station</strong> (Exit 1). The heritage-park entrance is next to the station''s well-known "monorail through the building" viewing platform.</li><li><strong>Liangjiang International Film City:</strong> Take the metro to <strong>Longfengxi Station</strong> (Exit 2), then transfer to bus <strong>980</strong> to the main entrance. A direct tourist shuttle also runs from downtown (e.g., Jiefangbei or Hongyadong) and takes about an hour.</li></ul><h3>Opening hours and tickets</h3><p>Many of Chongqing''s historic districts and public museums are free to enter, though some paid attractions require advance online booking. <strong>Please verify all hours and prices before your visit—these change often, and the details below should be treated as a starting point rather than a guarantee.</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Zhongshan Fourth Road:</strong> The street is open and free all day. The main venues—Gui Yuan, Zhougong Guan, and the Museum of the History of China''s Democratic Parties—are listed as open Tuesday to Sunday, 9:00 AM–5:00 PM (last entry 4:30 PM), closed Mondays (except public holidays). Admission is free, but a reservation via the official "Hongyan Scenic Area" WeChat account or tourism platform may be required.</li><li><strong>Longmenhao Old Street:</strong> The street is open and free all day. The main venues—the former U.S. Military Attaché''s Office and the "Chongqing·1937" theater—are listed as open Tuesday to Sunday, 10:00 AM–10:00 PM (last entry 9:30 PM), closed Mondays (except public holidays). Admission is free; a reservation via the official "Longmenhao Old Street" WeChat account may be required.</li><li><strong>Liziba–Sanma Road:</strong> The heritage park and Sanma Road area are open and free all day. Indoor venues, including the Gao Family Mansion, are listed as open Tuesday to Sunday, 9:00 AM–5:00 PM (last entry 4:30 PM), closed Mondays (except public holidays). Admission is free and no reservation is required.</li><li><strong>Liangjiang International Film City:</strong> Listed as open daily, 9:00 AM–6:00 PM (last entry 5:30 PM). Tickets can be booked in advance via the official "Liangjiang International Film City" WeChat account or bought on site; the adult ticket is listed at 40 yuan, with discounts for students, seniors, and children. Some immersive experiences inside carry an extra charge.</li></ul><h3>Dining</h3><p>Chongqing is known for its spicy hotpot, Sichuan-style street food, and a wide range of local specialties. All four districts offer options ranging from sit-down restaurants to street stalls and cafés.</p><ul><li><strong>Zhongshan Fourth Road:</strong> Several period-themed restaurants and cafés line the street, serving local Sichuan dishes—including Chongqing hotpot—as well as some modern takes. Many occupy historic buildings.</li><li><strong>Longmenhao Old Street:</strong> Look for stalls and small restaurants serving Chongqing street food such as grilled fish, spicy noodles, and cold dishes (Sichuan-style cold appetizers). Cafés and tea houses with outdoor terraces offer river views.</li><li><strong>Liziba–Sanma Road:</strong> Dining here is mostly casual, local home-style cooking—dishes like spicy stir-fried chicken, preserved pork, and local wonton soup. A few cafés and restaurants have terraces overlooking the river and the monorail.</li><li><strong>Liangjiang International Film City:</strong> A range of options inside, from period-themed restaurants to street stalls and cafés, mostly local Chongqing food with some Western and fusion choices. Many occupy replica buildings, which adds to the atmosphere.</li></ul><h3>Tips for your visit</h3><ul><li><strong>Wear comfortable shoes.</strong> Chongqing is a mountain city, and these districts are full of steep stone steps and cobblestone lanes. Non-slip walking shoes are essential; skip heels and hard-soled dress shoes.</li><li><strong>Plan ahead.</strong> The main museums and former residences can get busy, especially on weekends and public holidays. Booking in advance through official WeChat accounts or tourism platforms can save time in line.</li><li><strong>Check opening hours.</strong> Some indoor venues keep specific hours and may close for maintenance or on certain holidays. Confirm before you go.</li><li><strong>Bring sun and rain protection.</strong> Chongqing''s weather shifts quickly. A compact umbrella, hat, sunglasses, and sunscreen are all useful, especially for the outdoor districts.</li><li><strong>Consider late afternoon.</strong> The light is softer for photos, and you avoid the midday sun. In the evening, the street lamps and building lighting come on.</li><li><strong>Allow enough time.</strong> Each district has a lot to see; half a day per district is a reasonable estimate if you don''t want to rush.</li></ul><h2>In Closing</h2><p>Chongqing''s Republican-era districts are more than collections of old buildings—they offer a window onto one of the more turbulent periods in modern Chinese history. Each of the four in this guide gives a different view of it:</p><ul><li><strong>Zhongshan Fourth Road</strong> puts you inside the political history of the wartime years, in the rooms where decisions were made.</li><li><strong>Longmenhao Old Street</strong> pairs river views with older architecture and tells the story of the city''s contact with the outside world.</li><li><strong>Liziba–Sanma Road</strong> shows how the city''s builders worked with—and around—its steep terrain.</li><li><strong>Liangjiang International Film City</strong> offers a lighter, interactive take on the era.</li></ul><p>Walking through these districts, you catch the smell of old brick and greenery, the sound of the river, and traces of the past in small details throughout the city. It''s not only a tour of landmarks but a way to get a feel for Chongqing—its history, its culture, and its unusual setting. Enjoy the walk.</p>',
  '[{"icon":"📍","label":"Stops","value":"4 districts"}]'::jsonb,
  0,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
