INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'chongqing_palace_museum_southern_relocation',
  'chongqing',
  'A Warehouse That Saved a Nation''s Treasures',
  '故宫文物南迁纪念馆',
  'On the south bank of the Yangtze in Chongqing, tucked into the old Ciyun Temple neighborhood off Nanbin Road, stands a cluster of plain brick warehouses built into the hillside.',
  '🏛',
  'Culture',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>The Palace Museum Southern Relocation Memorial, Chongqing (Former Anderson &amp; Co. Warehouse)</h2><h3>A wartime history for foreign visitors</h3><p>On the south bank of the Yangtze in Chongqing, tucked into the old Ciyun Temple neighborhood off Nanbin Road, stands a cluster of plain brick warehouses built into the hillside. They look like nothing special. But during the Second Sino-Japanese War, four of these sheds hid 3,694 crates of the Forbidden City''s finest treasures — and every one of them came through the war unharmed. The site is now the Chongqing Palace Museum Southern Relocation Memorial (重庆故宫文物南迁纪念馆), opened to the public on June 11, 2021.</p><p>This is a short account of how those treasures came to be here, and what you can actually see today. Where the historical record is thin or contested, this guide says so rather than filling the gaps.</p><h2>Why the treasures had to move</h2><p>After Japan seized China''s northeast in the 1931 Mukden Incident and pushed toward Beiping (today''s Beijing), the Palace Museum began evacuating its collection south — first to Shanghai and Nanjing between 1933 and 1936. When full-scale war broke out in 1937 and Nanjing came under threat, the collection was split into three routes and moved west into the interior.</p><p>The middle route carried the largest share — roughly 9,300 crates — up the Yangtze by chartered steamer, through Wuhan and Yichang, reaching Chongqing in stages in 1938. Chongqing was the wartime capital, and it was bombed relentlessly for years, so the crates could not simply sit in the city center. They were divided among three sites on the safer south bank and downtown vaults: the Sichuan-Xikang Bank (川康平民商业银行, about 3,830 crates), the Jishi (Kiessling) Firm warehouse in Wangjiatuo (吉时洋行, about 1,814 crates), and the Anderson &amp; Co. warehouses (安达森洋行, 3,694 crates). This memorial occupies the third of those sites.</p><h2>The Swedish warehouse</h2><p>The Anderson warehouse was built by a Swedish merchant surnamed Anderson (安达森, sometimes rendered Andersen), who had traded on the Yangtze since Chongqing opened as a treaty port in 1891. His firm dealt in cured pork, bristles, and general goods, and it occupied several large sheds built into the riverside slope.</p><p>Two things made the site useful. First, the buildings were big, high-ceilinged, and solidly built. Second — and this is the detail every account emphasizes — Anderson was a citizen of Sweden, which stayed neutral in the war. According to the museum and standard histories, whenever Japanese aircraft came over during the bombing of Chongqing (which intensified from 1939), Anderson had a Swedish flag raised on the warehouse roof, and the buildings were spared. To make room for the crates, he reportedly ordered his own stock of cured meat cleared out. That order survives in local memory in Sichuanese dialect; the exact wording varies between retellings, so treat the famous "throw out the bacon" quote as folk memory rather than a verbatim record.</p><p>One caution worth flagging: some popular retellings claim Japanese command issued explicit orders never to overfly the warehouse, or that huge flags were spread across the open ground. The core fact — a Swedish flag on the roof, and the warehouse surviving intact — is well attested. The more elaborate versions are not clearly documented, and this guide does not assert them as fact.</p><h2>Guarding the crates</h2><p>Palace Museum staff and local workers unloaded the crates from river barges and logged each one into the warehouses. The real enemies during storage were not only bombs but Chongqing''s heat, damp, insects, and rats — any of which could destroy centuries-old silk scrolls and paintings.</p><p>The techniques the staff used are documented in the memoirs of the people who did the work. To keep crates off the damp floor and let air circulate, they built low wooden racks and, at some sites, set crates on smooth river pebbles — termites couldn''t climb the slick stones and had to build visible mud tunnels around them, which inspectors could spot and clear. Scrolls were periodically aired and sun-dried, always under supervision, with staff signing off each time. (Popular articles sometimes describe quicklime desiccant bags or a citywide telephone-linked alarm system at this specific warehouse; those details are not reliably sourced, so this guide leaves them out.)</p><p>The work was not without cost. During one urgent loading operation later in the relocation, a Palace Museum staff member named Zhu Xuekan (朱学侃) stepped into an open hold in the dark and fell to his death — a reminder that ordinary people carried real risk to protect these objects.</p><h2>Moving on, and going home</h2><p>Because Chongqing remained a bombing target and its climate threatened the collection, the middle-route treasures were moved again — to Angu Township (安谷乡) near Leshan in southern Sichuan, reached via the Min River. Leshan and nearby Emei sheltered the largest share of the southern-relocation collection for years, stored in local temples and clan halls with the help of villagers.</p><p>After Japan''s surrender in 1945, the scattered treasures were gathered back at Chongqing and shipped downriver to Nanjing beginning in 1947. The full southern-relocation saga — from the first crates leaving Beiping in 1933 to their eventual return — spanned well over a decade, crossed more than ten provinces, and involved some 19,000 crates. Sources differ on the exact end date: some Palace Museum accounts describe the collection returning to Beijing around 1950, while local histories note that portions did not reach Beijing until later in the 1950s. What every account agrees on is the outcome — that a collection of this size survived years of war with almost nothing lost, which is genuinely remarkable.</p><h2>The memorial today</h2><p>The site was restored between roughly 2017 and 2020 (with the architect Yung Ho Chang / Zhang Yonghe leading the design) and opened as a memorial on June 11, 2021. The deputy director of the Palace Museum, Yan Hongbin, attended the opening.</p><p>There are eight buildings in total — four are the original historic warehouses, the others rebuilt in a matching style. The exhibits trace the relocation with historical photographs, reproductions of packing lists and logbooks, and original wooden transport crates. Notably, the memorial holds almost no original artifacts — the treasures themselves are long back in Beijing and Taipei — so what you''re visiting is the *place* and its story, not a treasure display. Manage your expectations accordingly: this is a quiet, atmospheric historical site, not a blockbuster museum.</p><p>The restored complex also includes the well-known Corner Tower Café (角楼咖啡) in one of the buildings, with river views, and a shop selling Palace Museum–themed goods.</p><h2>Practical information</h2><p>Details below can change — confirm on the day of your visit, ideally through the memorial''s official channels or the WeChat mini-program, before relying on them.</p><ul><li><strong>Location:</strong> Ciyun Old Street, Nan''an District, Chongqing (南岸区慈云老街1号), on the south bank of the Yangtze near Ciqikou.</li><li><strong>Getting there:</strong> The memorial is on the south bank near the Ciyun Temple / Longmenhao historic district. Ciqikou Ancient Town sits across the river on the north bank, so if you plan to combine the two, check the actual river crossing and metro/bus connection rather than assuming a short walk. A taxi from central Chongqing is a straightforward option.</li><li><strong>Hours &amp;amp; admission:</strong> Admission has generally been free, with timed-entry reservation via the official WeChat mini-program, and the site closes one day a week. Exact hours, closing day, and reservation rules change — verify before you go.</li><li><strong>English services:</strong> English signage and English-language guiding have been offered, but availability (especially live English tours) varies. Don''t count on a live English tour without confirming in advance.</li><li><strong>Nearby:</strong> Ciqikou Ancient Town, the Chongqing bombing memorial sites, and the Yangtze River Cableway are all in the general area and can be combined into a day.</li></ul><h3>A note on sources and reliability</h3><p>This revision was written against Chinese-language institutional and press sources, including the Palace Museum, the Nan''an District government, provincial records (Sichuan sheng qing), Chinese Wikipedia''s entries on the memorial and the Anderson firm, and reporting in outlets such as PLA Daily and Sina Finance (the latter citing the memoir of Ouyang Daoda, who led the middle route).</p><p>Several vivid details common in tourist write-ups — flags spread on open ground, explicit Japanese no-fly orders for this warehouse, quicklime desiccant bags, a dedicated telephone alarm system, and a claim that this warehouse held the single most precious batch — could not be reliably confirmed and have been softened or removed. The core, well-attested facts are: the three Chongqing storage sites and their crate counts (3,830 / 1,814 / 3,694), the Swedish flag on the Anderson roof, the survival of the collection, the later move to Angu Township near Leshan, and the 2021 opening of the memorial. Where sources disagree (notably the final return date to Beijing), this guide flags the disagreement rather than picking one number.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  1,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
